{"title":"Rigid Body Motion Prediction with Planar Non-convex Contact Patch","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Accurately predicting rigid-body motion with intermittent, planar non-convex contact patches without ad hoc point-contact approximations and while preventing artificial interpenetration.","method":"Formulate a geometrically implicit time-stepping mixed nonlinear complementarity problem (MNCP) that solves contact detection and dynamics simultaneously. Model the non-convex contact by using the convex hull of the non-convex object and compute equivalent contact points (ECPs) as part of the solve via complementarity conditions derived from a closest-points optimization (Equations (8)–(12)), coupled with a maximum power dissipation/elliptic Coulomb friction model. Prove the ECP lies within the convex hull of the contact patch and that non-penetration holds at the end of each step (Propositions 1–2), even if the ECP may fall outside the physical patch."},{"problem":"Efficiently simulating bodies with multiple disjoint contact patches (e.g., furniture with multiple feet) without per-patch modeling that increases computational cost or yields non-unique force distributions.","method":"Replace multiple disjoint patches with a single convex-hull-based contact and solve one ECP/contact impulse jointly with the state in the MNCP. Empirically, this matches prior quadratic sliding and multi-patch MNCP models within 1e-8 in velocities while being far faster than the multi-patch MNCP (0.0053 s vs 0.0487 s per step) and only modestly slower than a specialized sliding-only model (0.0022 s per step)."},{"problem":"Automatically capturing transitions among surface, line, point contacts and separation during manipulation of non-convex objects while guaranteeing no penetration.","method":"Use the convex-hull, geometrically implicit formulation to recompute the ECP and contact mode each step without manual mode switching. In a T-shaped bar example, the simulation transitions among contact modes under varying forces/torques while maintaining no penetration (ECP z ≈ 0 within 1e-12), demonstrating seamless mode changes handled by the unified constraints."}]}
